Kubernetes is a container orchestration platform used to deploy, scale, and operate containerized applications in production environments.

It automates:

Scheduling
Scaling
Load balancing
Self-healing
Rollouts and rollbacks
Service discovery

Kubernetes is designed for distributed systems reliability.

Kubernetes Cluster Architecture

A Kubernetes cluster consists of two main parts:

Control Plane (Master)
Worker Nodes

Control Plane

The control plane manages the entire cluster and makes global decisions.

Components:

API Server
etcd
Scheduler
Controller Manager

API Server

The API Server is the entry point to the cluster.

All operations go through it:

kubectl
CI/CD pipelines
Controllers
Internal cluster components

The API server:

Validates requests
Updates cluster state
Stores data in etcd

Kubernetes follows a declarative model.

You declare desired state, Kubernetes reconciles it.

etcd

etcd is the key-value distributed database used by Kubernetes.

It stores:

Cluster state
Configuration
Secrets
Metadata

Important production concept:

etcd uses quorum consensus.

If quorum is lost, the cluster cannot update state.

This is why production clusters use:

3 or 5 etcd nodes.

Scheduler

The scheduler decides which node runs a pod.

It evaluates:

Resource availability
Scheduling rules
Constraints
Affinity rules
Taints and tolerations

Scheduling happens in two phases:

Filtering
Ranking

Filtering removes nodes that cannot run the pod.

Ranking chooses the best node.

Controller Manager

Controllers constantly compare:

Current State vs Desired State.

Examples of controllers:

Deployment Controller
Node Controller
Replication Controller
Endpoint Controller

This is called a control loop.

Worker Nodes

Worker nodes run the workloads.

Components:

Kubelet
Kube Proxy
Container Runtime

Kubelet

The kubelet is the node agent.

It:

Communicates with the API server
Ensures containers are running
Reports node health

If a container crashes, kubelet restarts it.

Container Runtime

The container runtime runs containers.

Examples:

containerd
CRI-O
Docker (legacy support)

Kube Proxy

Kube Proxy manages networking rules.

It enables:

Pod communication
Service load balancing

Kube Proxy modes:

iptables
IPVS

IPVS is more scalable in large clusters.

Kubernetes Core Concepts
Pods

The smallest deployable unit in Kubernetes is a Pod.

A Pod can contain:

One container (most common)
Multiple containers (sidecar pattern)

Example Pod:

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: nginx
spec:
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx

Pod characteristics:

Ephemeral
Scheduled once
Recreated when deleted

Pod Lifecycle

Understanding this is critical for SRE troubleshooting.

Pod states:

Pending
ContainerCreating
Running
Succeeded
Failed
CrashLoopBackOff
Terminating

Common production issue:

CrashLoopBackOff happens when:

Application crashes repeatedly.

Typical causes:

Bad configuration
Missing secrets
Application errors
Resource limits exceeded

ReplicaSets

ReplicaSets ensure a fixed number of pods are running.

Example:

replicas: 3

If one pod fails:

Kubernetes automatically creates a new one.

This provides self-healing.

Deployments

Deployments manage ReplicaSets and allow safe updates.

Key features:

Rolling updates
Rollbacks
Version control

Example:

strategy:
  type: RollingUpdate

Production deployment strategies:

Rolling Update
Blue/Green Deployment
Canary Deployment

Rolling update is the default.

Kubernetes Services

Pods are ephemeral, so we need stable networking.

Services provide a stable endpoint.

Service types:

ClusterIP
NodePort
LoadBalancer

ClusterIP

Default service type.

Accessible only inside the cluster.

Used for:

Internal microservices communication.

NodePort

Exposes service on node IP.

Port range:

30000–32767

Example:

nodeIP:30007

Used mainly for testing.

LoadBalancer

Used in cloud environments.

Cloud provider creates an external load balancer.

Example:

AWS ELB
GCP Load Balancer
Azure Load Balancer

Kubernetes Networking Model

Kubernetes networking is based on these principles:

Every Pod gets an IP address.
Pods communicate directly.
No NAT required between pods.

This is implemented through CNI plugins.

Common CNIs:

Calico
Flannel
Cilium
Weave

Advanced clusters use:

Cilium (eBPF-based networking).

Labels and Selectors

Labels organize Kubernetes objects.

Example:

env=production
app=frontend
tier=backend

Selectors allow grouping.

Example usage:

Services
Deployments
Network policies

Annotations

Annotations store metadata not used for scheduling.

Examples:

Build information
Monitoring metadata
Deployment notes

Taints and Tolerations

Taints prevent pods from being scheduled on nodes.

Example:

kubectl taint nodes node1 key=value:NoSchedule

Pods must define tolerations to run there.

This is used for:

Dedicated nodes
GPU workloads
Specialized hardware

Node Selectors and Node Affinity

Used to control pod placement.

Node Selector:

Simplest method.

Example:

run pods only on nodes labeled:

ssd=true

Node Affinity:

More advanced scheduling rules.

Types:

RequiredDuringScheduling
PreferredDuringScheduling

Namespaces

Namespaces isolate resources in the cluster.

Default namespaces:

default
kube-system
kube-public

Used for:

Multi-team environments
Resource isolation
Access control

Create namespace:

kubectl create namespace dev

Resource Quotas

Used to prevent one namespace from consuming all resources.

Example limits:

CPU
Memory
Pods
Services

Example configuration:

cpu: 10
memory: 20Gi
pods: 10

This is critical in multi-tenant clusters.

Resource Management

Pods define:

Requests
Limits

Requests = guaranteed resources
Limits = maximum resources allowed

Example:

resources:
  requests:
    cpu: "500m"
  limits:
    cpu: "1"
QoS Classes (Very Important for SRE)

Kubernetes assigns QoS classes.

Guaranteed
Burstable
BestEffort

If a node runs out of resources:

BestEffort pods are evicted first.

Probes (Health Checks)

Health checks are critical in production.

Types:

Liveness Probe
Readiness Probe
Startup Probe

Liveness Probe

Checks if the container is alive.

If it fails:

Container is restarted.

Readiness Probe

Checks if the application is ready to receive traffic.

If it fails:

Traffic is stopped.

Startup Probe

Used for slow-starting applications.

Prevents false failures during startup.

Example:

livenessProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /
    port: 80
Scheduling Deep Dive (Senior SRE Knowledge)

The scheduler considers:

Node capacity
Pod requirements
Affinity rules
Taints
Resource pressure

Advanced scheduling features:

Priority Classes
Preemption

Preemption allows high priority pods to evict lower priority ones.

Cluster Reliability Concepts

Production clusters must consider:

Failure domains
Node failure
Network partition
Control plane redundancy

High availability control plane includes:

Multiple API servers
Multiple etcd nodes
Load balanced API access

Troubleshooting Kubernetes (Real SRE Workflow)

Check cluster health:

kubectl get nodes

Check pods:

kubectl get pods -A

Describe pod:

kubectl describe pod podname

Check logs:

kubectl logs podname

Check events:

kubectl get events

Check scheduling problems:

kubectl describe pod

Look for:

FailedScheduling
ImagePullBackOff
OOMKilled

Real SRE Debugging Flow

Pod not starting:

1 Check pod state
2 Check events
3 Check node resources
4 Check scheduling constraints
5 Check image registry
6 Check secrets/configmaps
7 Check probes

Node problems:

1 Check node conditions
2 Check disk pressure
3 Check memory pressure
4 Check kubelet logs

Production Best Practices

Use readiness probes
Define resource limits
Avoid running everything in default namespace
Use autoscaling
Implement monitoring
Design stateless applications when possible

Observability (Essential for SRE)

Production clusters require observability.

Three pillars:

Metrics
Logs
Tracing

Typical stack:

Prometheus
Grafana
ELK stack
OpenTelemetry

Key SRE metrics:

Latency
Error rate
Traffic
Saturation

Also known as:

Golden Signals.

